            {
                "heading": "Isaiah 1:2-4 -- The Classic Riv Opening",
                "body": "Isaiah wastes no time. The very first words of his prophecy are a covenant lawsuit: 'Hear, O heavens, and give ear, O earth; for the LORD has spoken.' This is the classic riv summons, invoking the cosmic witnesses from Deuteronomy 32:1 and 4:26. Heaven and earth witnessed the Sinai covenant; now they are called to hear the indictment. The historical prologue follows immediately: 'Children have I reared and brought up' -- YHWH as the faithful parent who invested everything in his covenant children. Then the charge: 'but they have rebelled (pash'u) against me.' The word pesha' is treaty rebellion, not moral weakness. Isaiah drives the point home with devastating comparison: 'The ox knows its owner, and the donkey its master's crib, but Israel does not know, my people do not understand' (1:3). An ox -- an animal with no covenant, no Torah, no prophets -- recognizes who feeds it. Israel, with every advantage, does not even reach the intelligence of livestock. Verse 4 delivers the charge sheet: 'Ah, sinful nation, a people laden with iniquity, offspring of evildoers, children who deal corruptly! They have forsaken the LORD, they have despised the Holy One of Israel, they are utterly estranged.' Four charges, escalating in severity: sinful, iniquitous, evil in lineage, corrupt in practice. And the verdict: estranged -- the covenant relationship is broken."
            },
